Thank U, Next got two seats out of the top-10 list. One is imagine, the other is needy.
I do hate overly simple songs: cloying melodies consisted of banal, unimaginative motifs and too-obvious intentions are absolutely unforgivable. Referring the words of a professor&rsquo;s architecture appreciation course I&rsquo;ve taken two years ago, &ldquo;sometimes overly obvious &lsquo;signs&rsquo; or too straightforward expressions, despite appealing, are degrading for art.&rdquo;
BUT &mdash;- despite having shallow melodies (that one can literally anticipate the whole song after hearing the first few bars), needy sits on top of the list being simplicitly expressive and truthful.

Sabrina Carpenter&rsquo;s hit Nonsense is a great song, both artistically and commercially. The song gives a &ldquo;I-DONT-GIVE-A-SHIT&rdquo; (IDGAS) energy. The singer herself said in Genius VERIFIED interview
&ldquo;&hellip;we were hitting a lot of walls and we&rsquo;re like, you know what, let&rsquo;s just literally write nonsense, no joke. and that&rsquo;s how the song happened.&rdquo;
&ldquo;A lot of our justification for lyrics was well it&rsquo;s nonsense. so it doesn&rsquo;t have to make any sense at all and we just have fun.
